articles.push({
  slug: "how-to-tell-if-your-marketing-is-actually-working",
  title: "How to Tell if Your Marketing Is Actually Working",
  meta_title: "How to Tell if Your Marketing Is Actually Working",
  excerpt: "Followers and likes don't pay bills. Here are the metrics that actually tell you whether your marketing is driving business.",
  content_type: "authority_overview",
  content_pillar: "growth",
  tags: ["marketing ROI", "marketing metrics", "small business analytics"],
  body: 'You posted consistently for three months. Your follower count went up. You got some likes. A few comments. Maybe even a share or two. But the phone is not ringing any more than it was before. So you ask the question every business owner eventually asks: is any of this actually working?\n\nThe answer depends entirely on what you are measuring. And most business owners are measuring the wrong things.\n\n## The Vanity Metrics Trap\n\nFollowers, likes, and impressions feel good. They are visible, countable, and they go up in a satisfying way. But they do not pay your bills. A landscaper with 3,000 Instagram followers and zero inbound leads from those followers has a popular hobby, not a marketing channel.\n\nVanity metrics are not useless -- they indicate that content is being seen. But they are leading indicators at best and distractions at worst. The business owner who checks follower count daily but never looks at where new customers actually came from is optimizing for applause instead of revenue.\n\nHere is what matters instead.\n\n## Google Search Console: The Truth Detector\n\nSearch Console is free. It tells you exactly how many times your business appeared in Google search results, for which queries, and how many people clicked through to your site. This is the closest thing to a marketing lie detector that exists.\n\nIf your marketing is working, you will see two things over time: your total impressions increasing (Google is showing your business to more people) and your click-through rate holding steady or improving (the people who see you are interested enough to click). If impressions are flat after three months of consistent posting and blogging, something is wrong with the content strategy. If impressions are up but clicks are flat, your titles and descriptions need work.\n\nSearch Console also shows you which queries are driving traffic. A vet clinic that starts appearing for "emergency vet near me" or "best vet for anxious dogs" is building exactly the kind of search presence that converts to appointments.\n\n## Google Business Profile Views\n\nFor local businesses, GBP views are the single most important metric. This number tells you how many people saw your listing when they searched for something you offer in your area. GBP views lead directly to direction requests, phone calls, and website clicks.\n\nA business that is posting regularly to GBP, uploading photo series from completed work, and responding to reviews will see GBP views trend upward over 60-90 days. This is the metric that connects marketing activity to foot traffic and phone calls. If your GBP views are climbing, your marketing is working -- even if your Instagram likes are flat.\n\nTracPost publishes directly to Google Business Profile as part of every content cycle. When you capture a series of 5-10 project photos, the platform creates GBP posts, uploads photos to your listing, and manages review responses. These activities compound into GBP view growth that you can track week over week.\n\n## Organic Website Traffic\n\nPaid traffic disappears the day you stop paying. Organic traffic -- visitors who find you through search engines -- compounds. Every blog article you publish is a new entry point. Every page on your website is a keyword opportunity.\n\nThe metric to watch is organic sessions over time. Not total traffic (which includes direct visits and social clicks), but specifically the visitors who found you through Google, Bing, or other search engines. This number tells you whether your content is building long-term discoverability or just generating short-term clicks.\n\nA salon that publishes a blog article about "how to maintain balayage between appointments" might see that article start ranking after 30-60 days. Six months later, it is generating 50 visits per month from people actively searching for that information -- people who are now aware the salon exists and has expertise in exactly the service they need.\n\n## Customer Source Tracking\n\nThe most underrated metric in small business marketing is the simplest one: asking every new customer how they found you. "I saw you on Instagram." "I found you on Google." "My neighbor shared your post." "I saw your Google listing."\n\nThis low-tech signal is the ground truth that validates everything else. If three new clients this month said they found you on Google, and your GBP views are up, the system is working. If your follower count doubled but nobody mentions social media when asked, the followers are not converting.\n\nTrack this in a spreadsheet, a CRM, or a notebook by the phone. The pattern will become clear within 90 days.\n\n## The 60-90 Day Lag\n\nHere is what kills most marketing efforts: the results lag the work by 60-90 days. Google does not reward consistency instantly. Search rankings build over weeks. GBP prominence compounds over months. Blog articles take 30-60 days to get indexed and start ranking.\n\nThis means the marketing you do today shows up in your metrics two to three months from now. The business owner who posts consistently for six weeks, sees no immediate spike, and quits has abandoned the effort right before it would have started working. This is [why most small businesses quit social media](/blog/why-most-small-businesses-quit-social-media) -- they expect instant results from a system that rewards persistence.\n\n## What TracPost Shows You\n\nTracPost does not just publish content across Instagram, TikTok, Facebook, YouTube, Pinterest, LinkedIn, X, and Google Business Profile. It tracks the signals that matter. Your GBP view trends. Your posting consistency. Your review response rate. Your content reach across platforms. Your website traffic from the blog articles and SEO-optimized pages it generates and hosts.\n\nThe dashboard shows you the compounding effect -- how a photo series you captured three months ago is still driving search traffic through the blog article it became, still appearing in GBP results through the photos it added to your listing, still generating social engagement through the platform-native posts it created.\n\nMarketing that works does not feel dramatic in the moment. It feels quiet. The phone rings a little more. The "how did you find us" answers shift toward Google and social media. The website traffic chart tilts upward. The GBP views climb. And then one morning you realize you are booked three weeks out and you cannot remember the last time you bought an ad.\n\nThat is marketing that is actually working. And it starts with knowing what to measure.\n\n[Your competitors will notice before your customers do](/blog/why-your-competitors-will-notice-before-your-customers-do) -- because they are watching the same search results you should be watching. [See how TracPost tracks what matters](https://tracpost.com).'
});

