articles.push({
  slug: "tracpost-isnt-a-social-media-tool-heres-what-it-actually-is",
  title: "TracPost Isn't a Social Media Tool. Here's What It Actually Is.",
  meta_title: "TracPost Isn't a Social Media Tool. Here's What It Actually Is.",
  excerpt: "If you've been trying to figure out what category TracPost fits into, stop. The category doesn't exist yet.",
  content_type: "deep_dive",
  content_pillar: "growth",
  tags: ["tracpost", "content automation", "marketing platform", "category creation"],
  body: 'You have probably tried to compare TracPost to something you already know. A social media scheduler. A marketing agency. A website builder. An AI writing tool. None of those comparisons work, and the reason they do not work is the reason TracPost exists.\n\nEvery marketing tool on the market starts with the same assumption: you already have content. Hootsuite assumes you have posts to schedule. WordPress assumes you have articles to publish. Canva assumes you have designs to create. Mailchimp assumes you have emails to send. HubSpot assumes you have a marketing team to operate it.\n\nFor most small business owners, that assumption is wrong. You do not have content. You have a camera roll full of project photos that never became content. You have expertise that never became articles. You have a brand voice that never became captions. You have years of great work that nobody outside your existing client base has ever seen.\n\nThe entire marketing technology industry is built on a foundation that does not apply to you. TracPost starts where they all stop.\n\n## The Blank Screen Problem\n\nOpen Hootsuite. What do you see? A calendar with empty slots. It is waiting for you to create something. Open WordPress. An empty editor. It is waiting for you to write something. Open any social media scheduling tool, any content management system, any marketing automation platform. They all present you with the same thing: a blank screen and the implicit instruction to fill it.\n\nThis is the fundamental design failure of the entire category. These tools assume the hard part is distribution. It is not. The hard part is creation. The hard part is staring at your phone after a twelve-hour day and trying to write a caption that sounds professional. The hard part is building a website when you are not a writer or a designer. The hard part is figuring out what to post on eight different platforms when you barely have time to eat dinner.\n\nEvery tool you have tried failed you at the same point: the blank screen. TracPost does not have one.\n\n## Category by Category, Where They All Stop\n\nScheduling tools -- Hootsuite, Buffer, Later, Sprout Social -- solve distribution. They let you queue posts and publish them on a schedule. Useful, if you have posts to queue. For a business owner with no content pipeline, a scheduling tool is an empty calendar that reminds you of work you are not doing. You are paying for the privilege of seeing your own failure organized by date.\n\nMarketing agencies charge thousands per month and produce content that looks polished but feels generic. They do not know your business. They have never seen your work. They write captions from templates and use stock imagery because they do not have access to your real project photos. The content looks professional and converts nobody, because it has no authenticity. You are paying for volume that has no soul.\n\nContent management systems -- WordPress, Squarespace, Wix -- let you build a website. They do not write the content for it. They do not update it. They do not connect it to your social media or your Google Business Profile. You built a brochure site three years ago and it has not changed since. It tells Google you exist. It does not tell Google you are an authority.\n\nAI writing tools generate text. They do not know your brand voice, your service area, your competitive positioning, or what you actually did on the job site yesterday. They produce generic content that sounds like it was written by a machine, because it was. And they do not publish it anywhere. They hand you text and leave.\n\nSEO tools audit your website and tell you what is wrong. They do not fix it. They generate reports full of technical jargon and optimization scores that mean nothing to someone who installs furnaces for a living. You pay for diagnosis without treatment.\n\nMarketing automation platforms -- HubSpot, ActiveCampaign, Marketo -- are enterprise software designed for companies with marketing departments. They require dedicated operators, months of setup, and content that already exists. For a ten-person service company, they are a jet engine bolted to a bicycle.\n\nEvery one of these categories solves a real problem. None of them solves your problem. Your problem is that the content does not exist yet.\n\n## The Convergence\n\nTracPost replaces all of them. Not by doing each thing worse. By doing something none of them do at all: turning the work you already do into a complete marketing operation.\n\nYou capture a series of 5-10 photos of a completed project, an event, an appointment, a transformation. From that single input, TracPost produces everything:\n\nA brand playbook built from your voice, your positioning, and the way your business actually communicates. Not a template. Not a persona generator. A playbook derived from your real work and your real words.\n\nPlatform-native captions for every channel. The conversational tone Instagram rewards. The keyword-rich descriptions Google Business Profile needs. The professional framing LinkedIn expects. The visual hook TikTok demands. The community language Facebook favors. The aspirational copy Pinterest surfaces. The concise punch X amplifies. The searchable descriptions YouTube indexes. Each one written for the platform it will appear on.\n\nBlog articles that tell the story of the work. Not generic "five tips" content. Articles built from your actual projects, your actual expertise, your actual results. Content that ranks because it is specific, authentic, and useful.\n\nA hosted, SEO-optimized website that grows with every project you capture. No WordPress setup. No developer invoices. No quarterly update cycle. The site updates itself because your work updates it.\n\nPublishing across Instagram, TikTok, Facebook, YouTube, Pinterest, LinkedIn, X, and Google Business Profile. Not a single post copied to eight platforms. Platform-native content shaped for each channel.\n\nGoogle Business Profile management. Posts, photos, review responses. The ongoing work that keeps your listing active and your local ranking climbing.\n\nPaid amplification when something performs. When a post gains organic traction, TracPost can push it further with targeted campaigns. You do not set up ad accounts or configure audiences. The system identifies what is working and puts money behind it.\n\n## The Car and the Steering Wheel\n\nThink of it this way. Hootsuite is a steering wheel. WordPress is a set of tires. An agency is a driver you are paying to sit in a car that has no engine. AI writing tools are a fuel pump disconnected from everything else. SEO tools are a dashboard with warning lights and no mechanic.\n\nTracPost is the car. Engine, transmission, wheels, steering, fuel system, dashboard -- connected and running. You turn the key by capturing photos of your work. The car drives.\n\nThe reason you cannot figure out what category TracPost fits into is that the category does not exist yet. There is no name for a system that starts with a photo series and ends with a full marketing operation across eight platforms, a hosted website, managed listings, and paid amplification. The industry has not named it because nobody has built it before.\n\n## What You Stop Paying For\n\nWhen TracPost handles your marketing operation, line items start disappearing from your monthly expenses.\n\nThe social media manager you hired to post three times a week -- the one who uses stock photos because they do not have access to your real work. Gone.\n\nThe web developer you pay quarterly to update your site with new photos and copy. Gone.\n\nThe agency retainer that produces polished content with zero leads. Gone.\n\nThe SEO audit that tells you what is broken without fixing it. Gone.\n\nThe scheduling tool subscription for the empty calendar. Gone.\n\nThe ad spend you managed yourself, guessing at audiences and hoping something worked. Replaced by a system that identifies what performs organically and amplifies it with precision.\n\nYou stop paying for pieces of a system and start paying for the system.\n\n## What You Start Getting\n\nA marketing operation that runs on the work you already do. A website that grows. A Google listing that climbs. Social profiles that build trust before a prospect ever calls. Blog content that ranks for the searches your customers are making. Review responses that signal engagement. Paid campaigns that amplify proven content.\n\nAll of it generated from the photos you take on your phone. The photos you already take.\n\nTracPost is not a better version of something you have tried before. [It is not Hootsuite](/blog/i-already-tried-hootsuite-why-would-this-be-different). It is not [a marketing agency](/blog/you-dont-need-a-marketing-agency-you-need-a-marketing-engine). It is not [a social media manager](/blog/hiring-a-social-media-manager-vs-automating-it). It is the thing that replaces all of them.\n\nThe category does not exist yet. [TracPost is building it](https://tracpost.com).'
});

// ─── Run updates ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

async function main() {
  // Find the TracPost site
  const sites = await sql`
    SELECT s.id FROM sites s
    WHERE s.blog_slug = 'tracpost'
    LIMIT 1
  `;

  if (sites.length === 0) {
    console.error("No site found with blog_slug = 'tracpost'");
    process.exit(1);
  }

  const siteId = sites[0].id;
  console.log("Found TracPost site: " + siteId);
  console.log("Total articles to process: " + articles.length + "\n");

  let updated = 0;
  let inserted = 0;
  let errors = 0;

  for (const a of articles) {
    try {
      const existing = await sql`
        SELECT id, status FROM blog_posts WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
      `;

      const schemaJson = {
        "@context": "https://schema.org",
        "@type": "Article",
        headline: a.title,
        description: a.excerpt,
        author: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
        },
        publisher: {
          "@type": "Organization",
          name: "TracPost",
          url: "https://tracpost.com",
          logo: {
            "@type": "ImageObject",
            url: "https://tracpost.com/icon.png",
          },
        },
        datePublished: new Date().toISOString(),
        wordCount: a.body.split(/\s+/).length,
        keywords: a.tags.join(", "),
      };

      if (existing.length > 0) {
        // UPDATE -- preserve existing status
        await sql`
          UPDATE blog_posts
          SET
            body = ${a.body},
            title = ${a.title},
            meta_title = ${a.meta_title},
            excerpt = ${a.excerpt},
            meta_description = ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            tags = ${a.tags},
            content_type = ${a.content_type},
            content_pillar = ${a.content_pillar},
            schema_json = ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            updated_at = NOW()
          WHERE site_id = ${siteId} AND slug = ${a.slug}
        `;
        console.log("UPDATED: " + a.slug + " (status preserved: " + existing[0].status + ")");
        updated++;
      } else {
        // INSERT as draft
        await sql`
          INSERT INTO blog_posts (
            site_id, slug, title, body, excerpt,
            meta_title, meta_description, schema_json,
            tags, content_type, content_pillar,
            status, published_at, source
          ) VALUES (
            ${siteId}, ${a.slug}, ${a.title}, ${a.body}, ${a.excerpt},
            ${a.meta_title}, ${a.excerpt.slice(0, 155)},
            ${JSON.stringify(schemaJson)},
            ${a.tags}, ${a.content_type}, ${a.content_pillar},
            'draft', NULL, 'generated'
          )
        `;
        console.log("INSERTED: " + a.slug);
        inserted++;
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error("ERROR on " + a.slug + ": " + err.message);
      errors++;
    }
  }

  console.log("\nDone. Updated: " + updated + ", Inserted: " + inserted + ", Errors: " + errors);
}

main().catch(function(err) {
  console.error(err);
  process.exit(1);
});
